  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do low-income people survive in San Francisco with its high rent?",
  "response": "Surviving in San Francisco as a low-income individual can be especially challenging due to high housing costs. People manage in several ways, including:\n\n1. **Subsidized Housing**: Many low-income individuals apply for subsidized housing programs such as Section 8, which provides vouchers to help cover rent costs, or they seek out units within affordable housing developments.\n\n2. **Rent Control**: San Francisco has rent control laws that can help moderate rent increases for tenants in certain types of housing, allowing long-term residents to maintain more affordable rental prices.\n\n3. **Roommates and Shared Housing**: Sharing apartments or houses with multiple roommates helps to divide the cost of rent, utilities, and other expenses.\n\n4. **Living in Surrounding Areas**: Some people choose to live in nearby cities or suburbs where rent can be more affordable, often commuting to San Francisco for work.\n\n5. **Additional Jobs and Gig Economy**: Working multiple jobs or participating in the gig economy by driving for ride-sharing services, delivering food, or doing freelance work can supplement income.\n\n6. **Social Services and Nonprofits**: Utilizing food banks, free or low-cost meal programs, clothing assistance, and other services offered by local nonprofits helps low-income residents meet their basic needs.\n\n7. **Family Support and Community Networks**: Many rely on support from family and community connections, sharing resources and living spaces with relatives or community members.\n\n8. **Public Assistance Programs**: Programs such as CalFresh (food stamps), Medi-Cal (healthcare), and other state and federal aid provide vital support.\n\n9. **Financial Aid for Education**: Many benefit from scholarships, grants, and reduced tuition rates at educational institutions, enabling them to pursue higher education or vocational training to improve job prospects.\n\n10. **Cost-Saving Strategies**: Individuals frequently adopt frugal living strategies, such as taking public transportation instead of owning a car, shopping at discount stores, and finding creative ways to save money.\n\nNavigating life in such an expensive city often requires a combination of these strategies and significant resourcefulness.",
